('gen17Srv7Nme3_92626_1335119925', '1', 'This is my second note - edited', '<p>\r\n	How to make tag-clouds usable<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	In the majority of cases tag-clouds are only made into a usability nightmare by the user. Clouds are inherantly a good idea but stereotyped by poor implementation. For a tag cloud to be usable it should:<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be clear and concise<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have as few tags as possible, 10 is probably best, but certainly less than 30<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use sensible, descriptive tags. Using &quot;stuff&quot; as a tag isn&#39;t going to be helpful to anyone<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that even the least popular tags are still of a readable size<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be standards compliant (no inline styles)<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	For an example of an automatically generated tag-cloud that was less than useful, see my article on Seopher.com about the world&#39;s biggest tagcloud; one created on the previous implementation of the 9Rules blogging network. Remember, less is better.</p>', 'note, first, cloud, helloworld, debug', '2012-04-22 20:38:45', '2012-04-25 05:14:56', 'false', 3),
('gen17Srv7Nme3_7161_1335119991', '1', 'This is my third note', '<p>\r\n	Next make a php file and name it tag_cloud_gen.php . The php code written in following lines just make an array &lsquo;$words&rsquo; which has keyword in lower case &amp; its frequency association from input text. The pairs from the array are then feed into the mysql database &lsquo;tagcloud_db&rsquo; which has a table callet &lsquo;tags&rsquo; whose columns are listed above. On encountering error the mysql _errrno() returns error number. While feeding the word array to the tags table duplication may occour, because of the previous entries, so we check whether this is the case by comparing the number returned to &rsquo;1062&prime; which indicates duplicate field present in the table (the keyword coloumn of table has unique constraint). On encountering this we simply update the mysql database to include the count of this input word/tag too.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<font face="Georgia,\r\n                                                Times New Roman, Times,\r\n                                                serif">Hi Everyone,<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	</font><font face="Georgia, Times New\r\n                                                Roman, Times, serif">CAN YOU BELIEVE ITS ALREADY APRIL AND THE YEAR JUST SEEMS TO BE FLYING BY. Another season behind us&hellip;and indeed a major milestone for me as it is exactly 30 years since my father chartered the MSS ATLAS from Epirotiki Lines for one of the first ever local cruise seasons (1982-83 season) and put me in charge of its Sales &amp; Marketing strategy.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	I&rsquo;m sure there are some of you reading this today who would have cruised with the good ship ATLAS back then?&hellip;as we have many loyal folk who have cruised with us year after year since then. That whole season comprised of just 6 departures between 29 November, &lsquo;82 and 8 January, &rsquo;83&hellip; and our total passenger target was just 3,600 passengers. Amazing, when compared to the capacity of the MSC OPERA and MSC SINFONIA, with 2,100 passengers per cruise&hellip;and where in the coming season we will now embark 8, 400 passengers between Friday and Monday, every week from the end of November, 2012 until February, 2013.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	I had spent the previous nine years in Canada as a lumberjack, sawing railway ties for the American and Canadian railways and exporting timber to Japan. When I left Canada to escape the winter and to pay a brief visit to the family back home, I had no idea that visit would change my life forever. And so began a new career&hellip;a love affair with the sea, ships and shipping, which I am still passionate about and still doing 30 years on. There were many challenges, adventures, triumphs and disasters over the years but, looking back, it has been a wonderful experience working together with my brother, Clifford, and sister, Daphne, in the same company&hellip;building what is now a huge, unmatched local cruise industry.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Exciting times, I must say, but the future looks equally as challenging and exciting with bigger ships and longer seasons envisaged for the future. With cruising recognised as the fastest growing sector of the travel industry worldwide, MSC Starlight Cruises is perfectly positioned to ensure that South Africa does not lag behind. </font></p>', 'php, css, code, sql', '2012-04-22 20:39:51', '2012-04-25 05:43:02', 'false', 4),
('gen17Srv7Nme3_94876_1335330702', '1', 'My Fourth Note', '<p>\r\n	This is my first note. I really dont have much to say but to say that it is definitely a note, nahmean?? Update May 2011: Almost 4 years on, this post continues to get heaps of traffic and comments so i&rsquo;m going to attempt to answer some of the most FAQ. I have added the MySQL table structure and demonstrated how a basic search page would work to increment the search term counter. I&rsquo;ve also added some pretty CSS3 and added a last search date for each term. If you just want the files to download, skip to the end.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Sample Tag Cloud<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Today I wanted to make a tag cloud, but all my searching proved fruitless &ndash; so I decided to stop being lazy and just work it out myself!<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	First you&rsquo;ll need a database that stores the keywords and search terms.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Each time a user performs a search, we will check to see if the term has been searched before. If it has, we will increment the counter for that term. If the term has not been searched for before, we will insert the search term with a counter value of 1.</p>', 'php, css, code, sql', '2012-04-25 07:11:42', NULL, 'false', 5),
